For years I kept a watch to see whether anyone would claim the mythical honor of having been the central figure in this assumed recapture.
When, in 1882, on the publication of Kieffer's fascinating serial, The Recollections of a Drummer Boy, Sergeant John C. Kensill, Company F, 150th, posed as the longsought — for hero, I at once opened a correspondence with him;
but soon found that this comrade's mind was somewhat off its balance, and I subsequently learned that it was caused by a wound in his head.
